1
00:00:00,260 --> 00:00:03,700
Yassin's family moved from Iraq to England when he was just a young boy.

2
00:00:04,740 --> 00:00:08,880
Yassin did not want to leave his home in Samarra but his father said that it was best for the

3
00:00:08,880 --> 00:00:12,820
family because it was not safe to live there anymore and he wanted his son to grow up in

4
00:00:12,820 --> 00:00:18,000
a country that was accepting of all people. Yassin's father told his son that England was

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,420
a multicultural country where people lived and worked together regardless of race or religious

6
00:00:22,420 --> 00:00:28,559
beliefs. Although Yassin was not happy about leaving Iraq, he soon settled into his new life

7
00:00:28,559 --> 00:00:33,939
in a big city called London. London was very exciting with its tall buildings and museums,

8
00:00:34,439 --> 00:00:39,060
and Yassine especially liked the London Planetarium and the big River Thames with all of its old

9
00:00:39,060 --> 00:00:44,500
bridges. Yassine even made friends with a boy who lived next door, called Andrew.

10
00:00:45,500 --> 00:00:50,240
All summer long, Andrew and Yassine played in the park or went to the zoo with Andrew's mom.

11
00:00:51,280 --> 00:00:56,060
Andrew shared his toys and his comics with Yassine and told him all about his favorite superheroes.

12
00:00:56,060 --> 00:01:01,320
rose. They even built a camp in Yassin's back garden where they would hide from the grown-ups.

13
00:01:02,320 --> 00:01:07,099
The summer was a fun time and young Yassin soon felt quite at home in London even though it was

14
00:01:07,099 --> 00:01:13,000
a very big city and not nearly as sunny and hot as it was in Samara. His English got better and

15
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,780
better, especially with help from Andrew, although there were a lot of words that Yassin did not

16
00:01:17,780 --> 00:01:21,659
understand and he often felt silly because he couldn't speak as well as he would like.

17
00:01:21,659 --> 00:01:26,500
When September finally came around and the leaves began to fall from the trees,

18
00:01:26,900 --> 00:01:30,040
Yassin's father explained that it was time for his son to go to school.

19
00:01:31,060 --> 00:01:35,280
Yassin was 7 years old so he would be going to year 3 of the local primary school,

20
00:01:35,659 --> 00:01:50,831
the same year as his friend Andrew Although Yassin was very nervous about going to school his father and mother assured him that it would be a fun place where he would meet lots of new friends and learn lots of interesting new things English schools are supposed to be very good

21
00:01:51,091 --> 00:01:56,231
said Yassine's mother. And your English will get better in no time, assured his father.

22
00:01:57,312 --> 00:02:02,072
Yassine was still not convinced, but when Andrew knocked on the door that morning with a big smile

23
00:02:02,072 --> 00:02:06,492
on his face saying how fun it was going to be at school, Yassin felt much better because he

24
00:02:06,492 --> 00:02:13,331
trusted his friend. The two boys chatted all the way to the school gates. Andrew told Yassin about

25
00:02:13,331 --> 00:02:17,652
the playground and who was the best teacher and what boys were the most fun and what girls were

26
00:02:17,652 --> 00:02:23,211
pretty and how they often served custard for pudding at lunch times. Yassin did not know what

27
00:02:23,211 --> 00:02:28,231
custard was, but Andrew looked very excited about it so Yassin thought it must taste very good.

28
00:02:28,231 --> 00:02:33,572
But when the boys got to their class, things did not go how Yassin imagined they would.

29
00:02:34,491 --> 00:02:38,771
The teacher told Andrew to take a seat at the front of the class as she introduced Yassin to

30
00:02:38,771 --> 00:02:44,231
the rest of the children. He did not like standing up in front of the class and one boy shouted that

31
00:02:44,231 --> 00:02:49,972
he was a smelly foreigner. The boys and girls all laughed, and then another boy made fun of

32
00:02:49,972 --> 00:02:55,632
Yassin's accent when he was asked to say his name and where he came from. I can't understand him,

33
00:02:55,632 --> 00:03:03,372
miss. He can't even speak English, said the nasty boy. Finally, Yassine was allowed to take a seat

34
00:03:03,372 --> 00:03:07,771
at the back of the class but he wished that he was sitting next to Andrew as he felt very alone.

35
00:03:08,752 --> 00:03:12,931
The girls sitting beside him kept looking at him in a strange way that made Yassine uncomfortable,

36
00:03:13,372 --> 00:03:30,044
and during the lesson she put her hand up and asked the teacher if she could move places Yassine did not understand what he had done to offend the girl When the bell went it was time to go out into the playground All the children closed their books put on their coats and headed out of the door into

37
00:03:30,044 --> 00:03:35,463
the bright autumn sunshine. The teacher kept Yasin back for a moment and gave him a badge

38
00:03:35,463 --> 00:03:40,524
with his name on which she pinned to his jumper. There you go, she said with a smile.

39
00:03:41,524 --> 00:03:44,063
Now all of the children will be able to learn your name.

40
00:03:45,063 --> 00:03:49,204
Yassin thought that the badge looked silly, and when he went out into the playground all

41
00:03:49,204 --> 00:03:52,243
of the children began pointing. And laughing.

42
00:03:53,044 --> 00:03:56,963
You've got a girl's name, said a small boy with blonde curly hair.

43
00:03:57,984 --> 00:04:01,844
Yassin wanted to explain that it was not a girl's name but he was too nervous.

44
00:04:02,864 --> 00:04:08,144
When Yassin got nervous, his English was not very good and the words always got stuck in his throat.

45
00:04:09,104 --> 00:04:13,403
He was very sad and wanted to run out of the playground back to his mother and father and

46
00:04:13,403 --> 00:04:19,024
never return to school again. But just as he was about to run, he heard a familiar voice.

47
00:04:20,024 --> 00:04:24,764
Hi Yassine. And when he looked up there was Andrew standing right beside him.

48
00:04:25,704 --> 00:04:28,564
Andrew looked at the children gathered around and shook his head.

49
00:04:29,483 --> 00:04:34,863
What's wrong with you lot, he asked. I told my friend Yassine that school was fun.

50
00:04:35,564 --> 00:04:41,204
Why are you ruining it for him? He's different, said a very tall girl who was standing at the

51
00:04:41,204 --> 00:04:47,863
front of the crowd. So are you, said Andrew. You are the tallest girl in the whole school and you

52
00:04:47,863 --> 00:04:53,324
don't like it when people make fun of you, do you? Then Andrew looked at the boy with the curly hair.

53
00:04:54,064 --> 00:05:10,896
And you don like it when people say that you have girl hair he said to the boy We are all different and that is what makes us interesting What would life be like if we were all the same as one another There was silence among the children Then Yassin lifted his head high

54
00:05:11,896 --> 00:05:16,615
Boring, he said with a smile. That's right, exclaimed Andrew,

55
00:05:16,956 --> 00:05:20,115
returning his friend's smile. Really boring.

56
00:05:21,115 --> 00:05:26,755
And with that all of the children began to laugh. Really boring, they chanted at one another.

57
00:05:26,755 --> 00:05:32,416
Andrew went on to explain how he had spent the summer with Yassine, how they had built a camp

58
00:05:32,416 --> 00:05:37,435
together and played in the park, and how Yassine preferred Batman to Superman, and how he really

59
00:05:37,435 --> 00:05:42,475
was different because he didn't even like hot dogs. The children all laughed some more and

60
00:05:42,475 --> 00:05:46,136
soon everybody was talking about all the things that made them different from one another.

61
00:05:47,156 --> 00:05:51,596
Peter Jenkins even lifted up his jumper and showed everybody a big purple birthmark on

62
00:05:51,596 --> 00:05:56,016
the front of his belly. Now that's what I call different, he said triumphantly.

63
00:05:56,755 --> 00:06:03,216
I bet none of you have a big birthmark like mine. When break time was over, Andrew put his hand up

64
00:06:03,216 --> 00:06:07,315
in class and suggested to the teacher that they should spend the lesson talking about how great

65
00:06:07,315 --> 00:06:11,036
it was that everybody was so different from everybody else and how people came to England

66
00:06:11,036 --> 00:06:16,435
from all over the world to begin a new life just like his friend Yassine. The teacher agreed that

67
00:06:16,435 --> 00:06:20,716
it was important to be an individual, and she also said how wonderful it was that the whole

68
00:06:20,716 --> 00:06:26,255
of Britain was such a multicultural island. Yassine wrote these two words down in his book

69
00:06:26,255 --> 00:06:31,776
and promised himself that he would learn them both and remember them always. He also wrote the word

70
00:06:31,776 --> 00:06:37,456
friend in his book. He already knew what that meant, but he just wanted to write it down because

71
00:06:37,456 --> 00:06:42,016
he felt so lucky to have a good friend like Andrew who stood up for people and did not judge them

72
00:06:42,016 --> 00:06:43,115
just because they were different.

